\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Growth rate: variation with temperature
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Phytoplanktonic growth rates are highly variable, in situ or in experimental
 conditions.
 An example of such variability appears in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "balzano_effects_2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For ten strains of one genus only (
\shape italic
Skeletonema
\shape default
), and in the same experimental conditions, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "balzano_effects_2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have been able to detect growth rates between 0.5 and 1.25 day
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

, which corresponds more generally to the values found in the literature
 (between 0.2 and 1.78 for diatoms in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "reynolds2006ecology"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, even reaching 3 in the meta-analysis of 308 experiments by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "edwards_light_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

; this can be much lower for dinoflagellates).
 These growth rates are maximum, fixed values for isolated species in laboratory
 conditions.
 Most of the time, they correspond to fixed temperature conditions, or to
 only a small set of values.
 These observations therefore cannot accomodate realistic, seasonal environment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this context, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bissinger_predicting_2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 based their study on a seminal work by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "eppley_temperature_1972"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to compute the maximum possible growth rate depending on the temperature.
 The relationship between temperature and maximum growth rate, evaluated
 on a large database
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
1,501 data points from several studies
\end_layout

\end_inset

, is then 
\begin_inset Formula $r(T)=0.81\text{e}^{0.0631T},$
\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 in °C.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Previously: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

This represents the daily growth rate under a continuous irradiance and
 can therefore be at least halved because mean daylight is around 12 hours.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Actually, this was the case for the Eppley curve but Bissinger is based
 mostly on the LPD dataset, which was not always taken in maximum growth
 condition - replete nutrient and light.
 So the correction was not right.
\end_layout

\end_inset

In this case, growth rates vary between 0.81 and 3.9 day
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 for temperatures between 0 and 25°C, in line with previous observations.
 However, these values only illustrate a maximum, exponential growth which
 cannot be realistic for species with different niche temperatures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equation of 
